<section id="section-4">
<title> Kinetic friction
</title>


<para id="element-51">If the external force parallel to contact surface exceeds maximum static friction, then the body starts moving over underlying surface. It does not mean, however, that friction between surfaces disappears. New contact points between surfaces come in contact, some of which are momentarily joined and then broken on continuous basis. The friction force is dropped slightly (almost instantly); but remains constant - independent of the velocity of the body. 
</para>
<para id="element-52">
We denote kinetic friction force as 
<m:math>
<m:msub>
<m:mi> F </m:mi>
<m:mi> k </m:mi>
</m:msub>
</m:math>
 and corresponding friction coefficient as 
<m:math>
<m:msub>
<m:mi> μ </m:mi>
<m:mi> k </m:mi>
</m:msub>
</m:math>
